John Edward: Linguistic skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a trajectory of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced with individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer a service of the highest level to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, for the career they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages are still a very popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to establish relationships and generate trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are leading the rankings with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages received the A-higher grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, remain in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculums of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Competence Commission revealed that of the reasons employers gave to the fact that it cost them to cover the vacancies, 17% were attributed to a lack of linguistic skills.
Therefore, linguistic skills are becoming increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
As there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these competencies are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the race a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this one.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person in front of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov of over 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children the best chances of finding an important job.
In Scotland, there is diversity between schools in terms of the languages they are taught.
Some schools focus more on the more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are thought to be more important for the UK in the future, by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, you will always be able to choose from a number of languages in independent schools, which have specialist teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In today’s global commercial environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of vital importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered “international communicative competences”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
