The course, implemented for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's health services, said the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a bedroom, where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, bamboo and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how it affects sports performance in lack of sleep, and about the importance of maintaining a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase their risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Then, a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride to stay awake all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure that students suffer make sleep deprivation an ever-increasing problem.
Ensure that enjoying a good quality sleep for enough time should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in annoying mode and makes them constantly studying.
