Red tide update: concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed proliferation conditions are being reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a lower concentration.
The proliferation of the red tide extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from the north of Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
You can find spots 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average coastal or coastal concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County over the past week, low to high coastal concentrations in Hillsborough County, low to high coastal concentrations in Manatee County, low to high coastal concentrations at low coastal or low coastal concentrations in Charlo County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeastern Florida.
